lism -- tAppendix 3 Empty Spaces and the Multiple Modernities of Nationalism -- tAppendix 4 The Social Genesis of Anzac Nationalism -- tAppendix 5 The Australian Society of the State: Egalitarian Ideologies and New Directions in Exclusionary Practice -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe civil war in Sri Lanka and the part that nationalism seemed to play in it inspired the writing of this book some twenty-three years ago. The argument was developed through a comparative analysis of nationalism in Sri Lanka with the author’s native Australia. At the time this constituted an innovative approach to comparison in anthropology, as well as to nationalism and its possibilities. It was not based on differences but on the way in which perspectives from within the two nationalisms, when seen side-by-side, could present an understanding of their implication in producing the violence of war, racism, and social exclusion. The book has lost none of its importance and urgency as proven by the chapters in the Appendix, written by top scholars working in Sri Lanka and in Australia. These contributions bring together new material and critically explore the book’s themes and their continued relevance to the various trajectories in nationalist processes since the first publication of the book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aEthnic relationsvCase studies. 0aNationalismvCase studies. 0aPolitical culturezAustralia. 0aPolitical culturezSri Lanka. 0aState, ThevCase studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aBastin, Rohan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKapferer, Bruce, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorris, Barry, econtributor.4ctb4htt